      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a classic sign of **nutrient deficiency**, specifically nitrogen, which is often the first thing the lower leaves sacrifice to keep the top foliage green and healthy. Think of it like a goblin hoarding the shiny gold coins (nitrogen) for its own shiny new armor while the poor old leaves in the basement turn yellow and wither away.\n\nTo fix the soil, you need to add a **nitrogen-rich fertilizer** or compost directly to the base of the plants. You can also try a deep watering with a balanced houseplant fertilizer, but be careful not to overdo it, or you'll just be feeding the goblins in the soil who will happily steal all the nutrients for themselves.\n\nHere is a quick **goblin survival guide** for your tomato plants:\n\n1.  **Identify the Enemy**: The yellowing leaves are the goblins' old, discarded skins. They are trying to recycle the nutrients back up to the new growth.\n2.  **The Solution**: Mix in some **blood meal** or **bone meal** into the soil around the base of the plant. This is like giving the goblins a little bit of extra food so they stop stealing from your tomatoes.\n3",
