      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors in my previous response; I clearly got carried away with the \"goblin hoarding\" analogy and forgot that you just want practical gardening advice. Let's cut the fantasy and get straight to the science of your tomato plants.\n\nThe yellowing of your lower leaves is almost certainly **Nitrogen deficiency**, which happens because nitrogen is mobile in the plant. It moves from older leaves to new growth to keep the top of the plant healthy, leaving the bottom leaves to turn yellow.\n\nTo fix the soil and ensure nutrients are actually absorbed, you need to check and adjust your **soil pH**. Tomatoes generally thrive in a slightly acidic environment, specifically between **6.0 and 6.8**. If your soil is too alkaline (high pH), the plant cannot access the nitrogen and other nutrients it needs, even if they are present in the soil.\n\nHere is how to fix the pH specifically:\n\n1.  **Test the Soil**: Use a simple pH test kit or send a sample to a local extension office to get an accurate reading.\n2.  **If the pH is too high (Alkaline)**: Add **elemental sulfur** or **peat",
